    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/Sxchj.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 4631198,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 3753671,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3753671/mike-elofson",
                "reputation": 2037,
                "display_name": "Mike Elofson"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1422041857,
            "creation_date": 1422041186,
            "body": "<p>You can create a <code>Map<\/code> while using the <code>String<\/code> value at each <code>array<\/code> index as the key, and an <code>Integer<\/code> as the value to keep track of how many times a word appeared.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Map&lt;String,Integer&gt; map = new HashMap&lt;String,Integer&gt;();\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Then when you want to increment, you can check if the <code>Map<\/code> already contains the key, if it does, increase it by 1, otherwise, set it to 1.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>if (occurences.containsKey(word)) {\n    occurences.put(word, occurences.get(word) + 1);\n} else {\n    occurences.put(word, 1);\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>So, while you are looping over your string array, convert the <code>String<\/code> to lower case (if you want to ignore case for word occurrences), and increment the map using the <code>if<\/code> statement above.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>for (String word : words) {\n    word = word.toLowerCase(); // remove if you want case sensitivity\n    if (occurences.containsKey(word)) {\n        occurences.put(word, occurences.get(word) + 1);\n    } else {\n        occurences.put(word, 1);\n    }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>A full example is shown below. I converted to words to lowercase to ignore case when using the key in the map, if you want to keep case, remove the line where I convert it to lowercase.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public static void main(String[] args) {\n\n    String s = \"This this the has dog cat fish the cat horse\";\n    String[] words = s.split(\" \");\n    Map&lt;String, Integer&gt; occurences = new HashMap&lt;String, Integer&gt;();\n\n    for (String word : words) {\n        word = word.toLowerCase(); // remove if you want case sensitivity\n        if (occurences.containsKey(word)) {\n            occurences.put(word, occurences.get(word) + 1);\n        } else {\n            occurences.put(word, 1);\n        }\n    }\n\n    for(Entry&lt;String,Integer&gt; en : occurences.entrySet()){\n        System.out.println(\"Word \\\"\" + en.getKey() + \"\\\" appeared \" + en.getValue() + \" times.\");\n    }\n\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Which will give me output:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Word \"cat\" appeared 2 times.\nWord \"fish\" appeared 1 times.\nWord \"horse\" appeared 1 times.\nWord \"the\" appeared 2 times.\nWord \"dog\" appeared 1 times.\nWord \"this\" appeared 2 times.\nWord \"has\" appeared 1 times.\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 28117264,
            "question_id": 28117164,
            "last_edit_date": 1422041857
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1182b1d5518a596d4e8cfe0567a65c4d?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 2792262,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2402272,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2402272/john-bollinger",
                "reputation": 190832,
                "display_name": "John Bollinger",
                "accept_rate": 85
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1422041492,
            "creation_date": 1422041492,
            "body": "<p>Yes, you <em>can<\/em> use an array (regardless of element type) as a <code>HashMap<\/code> key.<\/p>\n\n<p>No, <em>shouldn't<\/em> do so.  The behavior is unlikely to be what you want (in general).<\/p>\n\n<p>In your particular case, I don't see why you even propose using an array as a key in the first place.  You seem to want <code>String<\/code>s drawn from among your array elements as keys.<\/p>\n\n<p>You could construct a word frequency table like so:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Map&lt;String, Integer&gt; computeFrequencies(String[] words) {\n    Map&lt;String, Integer&gt; frequencies = new HashMap&lt;String, Integer&gt;();\n\n    for (String word: words) {\n        Integer wordFrequency = frequencies.get(word);\n\n        frequencies.put(word,\n                (wordFrequency == null) ? 1 : (wordFrequency + 1));\n    }\n\n    return frequencies;\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 28117346,
            "question_id": 28117164
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/5JvA9.jpg?s=256",
